<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-334-798  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 334 798.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  April 9 1990 v218 n15 p8(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Appeals court reverses Greene on information services ban. (HaroldGreene)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mason, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A federal appeals court ruled that US District Judge Harold Greeneapplied a legal standard that was too strict when he decided tomaintain the information services ban, against Bell regionalholding companies (RHCs), in the Modified Final Judgement (MFJ).andO;Greene must now reconsider using a less demanding standard anddetermine whether RHCs entry into information services is withinthe legal definition of 'public interest.' While Greene reviewsthe issues, he can still maintain the ban.andP;  Judges were concernedabout the scope of the ban.andP;  The appeals court also wants Greeneto consider whether the anti-competitive risks will outweigh theadministrative burdens of a limited prohibition.andP;  Most of the RHCswere pleased with the ruling.andP;  The American Newspaper PublishersAssociation, an opponent of RHCs entry into information services,vowed it will fight the RHCs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone companiesInformation servicesLegal IssuesTelecommunications.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Harold Greene. (portrait)Person:    Greene, Harold (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>